  "summary": "Megan Barnard shares a memory of her mother's devastation following Betty's death, noting her mother bought stockings for her that she never got to use. This creates an emotional bond between Megan and Franklin Clark. Tora Grey shifts the conversation to future planning, prompting Franklin Clark to suggest that the group join forces once a fourth letter arrives.\n\nHercule Poirot proposes several lines of inquiry. He suggests Megan use an \"offensive strategy\" by arguing with a waitress named Milly Higley to provoke her into revealing her true feelings about Betty. He also suggests Donald Fraser show interest in the waitress. Poirot recommends Mary interview children near her aunt's shop, as they may have seen people entering the shop. Tora Grey notes that the third letter was postmarked from Putney (SW15), suggesting the killer, ABC, is from London. Franklin Clark proposes placing a provocative advertisement to attract ABC's attention, an idea Poirot deems worth trying despite potential danger. Franklin records the plan: Megan and Milly Higley, Donald Fraser and Milly Higley, the children of Andersson, and the advertisement.\n\nAfter the group disperses, Poirot reveals to Hastings that he manipulated the conversation to give the group a sense of purpose. He observes the interpersonal tensions, noting Franklin's sudden rapport with Megan and Tora Grey's anger. Tora Grey returns to speak with Poirot privately, clarifying that she did not leave Compiegne willingly. She explains that while Franklin is loyal, it was the ill and delusional Mrs. Clarke who insisted she leave the house due to irrational suspicion.",
